course.courseTitle: Principles of Accounting: Introduction to Financial Accounting Principles

templateAssets.content:
The Financial Actuarial Mathematics major concerns the application of mathematics to finance, the actuarial field, and related areas.


Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major. Transfer students are admitted as a Pre-Financial Actuarial Mathematics major and must apply to the Financial Actuarial Mathematics major after their first term at UCLA.


To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer:

  • One and a half years of Calculus through Multivariable, and
  • Either Linear Algebra or Differential Equations.

Completion of the full calculus series including linear algebra and differential equations and one introductory course in C++ is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED.

All courses must be taken for a letter grade.


For more information regarding this major and UCLA's selection process, visit https://ww3.math.ucla.edu and https://admission.ucla.edu.


PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy preparation for this major at UCLA major, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses.

The AP Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus AB exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
  • A score of 4 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A and 31B.


The IB Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 6 or higher on the IB HL Math Analysis & Approaches exam will satisfy MATH 31A.
